01:44.387 --> 01:47.618
- It's 2 o'clock in the morning.
- Oh, George!

01:47.824 --> 01:49.121
Well, it is.

01:51.127 --> 01:52.287
What a cluck you are!

01:53.296 --> 01:54.957
It's late, you know. It's late.

04:16.606 --> 04:18.096
What a dump!

04:20.442 --> 04:23.606
Hey, what's that from? “What a dump! “

04:24.447 --> 04:25.778
How would I know?

04:26.282 --> 04:28.944
Oh, come on, what's it from?
You know!

04:31.621 --> 04:34.283
What's it from, for Christ's sake?

04:34.624 --> 04:36.114
What's what from?

04:36.960 --> 04:39.952
I just told you. I just did it.

04:40.296 --> 04:42.287
“What a dump! “

04:43.299 --> 04:45.290
Huh? What's that from?

04:45.635 --> 04:47.466
I haven't the faintest idea.

04:48.137 --> 04:49.331
Dumbbell!

04:50.073 --> 04:52.132
It's from some Bette Davis picture...

04:52.475 --> 04:54.466
...some goddamn Warner Brothers epic.

04:54.811 --> 04:58.804
Martha, I can't remember all the films
that came out of Warner Brothers.

04:59.148 --> 05:02.140
Nobody's asking you to remember
every Warner Brothers epic.

05:02.485 --> 05:04.646
Just one single little epic.
That's all.

05:05.488 --> 05:07.820
Bette Davis gets peritonitis at the end.

05:08.157 --> 05:10.819
And she wears a fright wig
throughout the picture.

05:11.160 --> 05:13.321
She's married to Joseph Cotten
or something.

05:13.663 --> 05:14.652
Somebody.

05:16.499 --> 05:20.333
She wants to go to Chicago because
she loves that actor with the scar.

05:21.004 --> 05:22.096
She gets sick...

05:22.338 --> 05:24.499
...and sits down at her dressing table...

05:24.841 --> 05:26.331
What actor? What scar?

05:26.676 --> 05:29.509
I can't remember his name!
What's the picture?

05:29.846 --> 05:31.837
I want to know the name of the picture.

05:33.349 --> 05:35.681
She gets this peritonitis...

05:36.686 --> 05:39.849
...and decides to go to Chicago anyway.

05:40.523 --> 05:42.514
“Chicago”! It's called “Chicago.”

05:45.294 --> 05:46.352
What is?

05:47.864 --> 05:49.764
I mean the picture. It's “Chicago.”

05:50.533 --> 05:52.524
Oh, good grief!

05:53.536 --> 05:55.197
Don't you know anything?

05:56.039 --> 05:58.701
“Chicago” was a '30s musical...

05:59.042 --> 06:02.534
...starring little Miss Alice Faye.
Don't you know anything?

06:03.880 --> 06:04.869
This picture...

06:05.715 --> 06:09.378
...Bette Davis comes home from
a hard day at the grocery store...

06:09.719 --> 06:11.380
She works in a grocery store?

06:12.722 --> 06:15.384
She's a housewife. She buys things.

06:17.560 --> 06:19.050
She comes with the groceries...

06:19.729 --> 06:22.391
...and she walks into
the modest living room...

06:22.732 --> 06:26.566
...of the modest cottage
modest Joseph Cotten set her up in.

06:26.903 --> 06:27.733
Are they married?

06:28.905 --> 06:31.738
Yes, they're married.
To each other, cluck!

06:32.575 --> 06:37.239
And she comes in
and she looks around this room...

06:38.915 --> 06:41.076
...and she sets down her groceries.

06:41.751 --> 06:42.911
And she says...

06:44.087 --> 06:45.918
...”What a dump! “

06:52.261 --> 06:53.751
She's discontent.

06:56.933 --> 06:58.423
What's the name of the picture?

06:59.268 --> 07:00.758
I really don't know.

07:01.104 --> 07:02.435
Well, think!

07:02.772 --> 07:03.761
I'm tired, dear.

07:04.107 --> 07:07.440
I don't know why you're tired.
You didn't do anything today.

07:07.777 --> 07:09.574
- I'm tired.
- You didn't have classes.

07:09.779 --> 07:13.613
If your father didn't always set up
these Saturday night orgies...

07:13.950 --> 07:15.781
Well, it's just too bad about you.

07:16.119 --> 07:17.780
Well, that's how it is anyway.

07:18.121 --> 07:22.455
You didn't do anything. You never do.
You never mix!

07:22.792 --> 07:24.453
You just sit around and talk.

07:25.294 --> 07:29.287
What do you want me to do?
Bray at everyone all night like you do?

07:29.632 --> 07:31.293
I don't bray!

07:31.634 --> 07:33.625
All right, you don't bray.

07:34.637 --> 07:36.127
I did not bray.

07:36.472 --> 07:37.962
I said you didn't bray!

07:40.143 --> 07:41.132
Fix me a drink.

07:42.645 --> 07:43.805
Haven't you had enough?

07:44.480 --> 07:46.812
I said fix me a drink!

07:49.152 --> 07:52.815
Well, I don't suppose a nightcap
would kill either of us.

07:53.990 --> 07:55.981
A nightcap? Are you kidding?

07:57.660 --> 07:58.786
We've got guests.

08:01.097 --> 08:01.756
Got what?

08:04.500 --> 08:06.991
Guests. Guests!

08:09.338 --> 08:13.331
Yeah, guests. People.
We've got guests coming over.

08:14.010 --> 08:14.874
When?

08:15.878 --> 08:16.867
Now.

08:17.847 --> 08:20.179
Good Lord, Martha,
do you know what time it is?

08:22.018 --> 08:23.349
Who's coming over?

08:23.686 --> 08:25.779
- What's-their-name.
- Who?

08:27.423 --> 08:29.152
Who's what's-their-name?

08:30.359 --> 08:33.192
I don't know their name, George.

08:33.529 --> 08:38.193
We met tonight. They're new. He's
in the math department or something.

08:38.534 --> 08:41.025
I don't remember
meeting anybody tonight.

08:41.236 --> 08:42.828
Well, you did.

08:43.039 --> 08:45.872
Of all the asinine...
Who are these people?

08:46.209 --> 08:49.042
He's in the Math Department.

08:49.245 --> 08:50.109
Who?

08:50.546 --> 08:55.210
He's in the Math Department.
He's young and he's blond...

08:55.885 --> 08:57.546
He's good-looking, well-built?

08:57.887 --> 09:00.378
Yes, good-looking, well-built.

09:01.724 --> 09:03.715
- It figures.
- What?

09:03.926 --> 09:05.052
Nothing.

09:05.561 --> 09:09.053
His wife's a mousy little type
without any hips or anything.

09:10.399 --> 09:11.388
Remember them now?

09:11.901 --> 09:14.734
I guess so. But why do they
have to come over now?

09:15.071 --> 09:18.040
Because Daddy said
we should be nice to them, that's why.

09:18.908 --> 09:21.376
- Daddy said we should be nice to them.
- Why now...?

09:21.577 --> 09:24.239
Because Daddy said
we should be nice to them!

09:24.580 --> 09:28.072
He didn't mean we were supposed
to stay up all night with them.

09:28.417 --> 09:30.408
We could have them over
some Sunday.

09:30.753 --> 09:33.085
Well, never mind.
Besides, it is Sunday.

09:34.257 --> 09:36.088
Very early Sunday.

09:36.926 --> 09:39.520
- It's ridiculous!
- Well, it's done.

10:05.788 --> 10:08.951
Where are they?
If we've got guests, where are they?

10:09.292 --> 10:10.782
They'll be here soon.

10:11.127 --> 10:13.425
What'd they do, go home
and get some sleep first?

10:14.297 --> 10:16.288
They'll be here.

10:16.499 --> 10:17.864
I wish you'd tell me...

10:18.100 --> 10:21.160
...about things. Stop springing
things on me all the time.

10:21.637 --> 10:24.333
I don't spring things
on you all the time.

10:24.640 --> 10:28.303
You really do! You're always
springing things on me.

10:29.145 --> 10:30.442
Always.

10:31.280 --> 10:35.114
Poor Georgie Porgie put-upon-pie.

10:41.791 --> 10:44.954
What are you doing? Are you sulking?

10:46.462 --> 10:49.954
Let me see. Are you sulking?

10:50.299 --> 10:52.631
Is that what you're doing?

10:53.302 --> 10:54.633
Never mind.

10:57.473 --> 10:58.963
Just don't bother yourself.

11:07.983 --> 11:12.647
Who's afraid of Virginia Woolf,
Virginia Woolf, Virginia Woolf?

11:19.495 --> 11:22.987
What's wrong? Didn't think it's funny?
I thought it was a scream.

11:23.332 --> 11:24.492
It was all right.

11:24.834 --> 11:26.995
You laughed when you heard it
at the party.

11:27.336 --> 11:28.826
I smiled. I didn't laugh.

11:29.171 --> 11:31.503
You laughed your goddamn head off!

11:31.841 --> 11:32.671
It was all right.

11:33.008 --> 11:34.669
It was a scream.

11:35.010 --> 11:37.843
It was very funny, yes.

11:38.714 --> 11:40.272
You make me puke.

11:41.851 --> 11:43.682
You make me puke.

11:44.787 --> 11:46.448
Wasn't a very nice thing to say.

11:46.856 --> 11:48.346
That wasn't what?

11:48.691 --> 11:50.522
A very nice thing to say.

11:50.860 --> 11:52.521
Oh, I like your anger.

11:53.028 --> 11:56.361
I think that's what I like
about you most.

11:56.699 --> 11:58.030
Your anger.

12:01.137 --> 12:03.605
You are such a simp!

12:03.906 --> 12:05.703
You haven't got...

12:07.877 --> 12:09.139
...the what?

12:10.913 --> 12:11.675
Guts?

12:13.716 --> 12:15.047
Phrase-maker.

12:36.772 --> 12:39.741
You never put any ice in my drink.
Why is that?

12:40.743 --> 12:43.735
I always put ice in your drinks.
You eat it, that's all.

12:44.079 --> 12:48.573
It's this habit you've got of chewing
on your ice cubes like a cocker spaniel.

12:50.753 --> 12:52.243
You'll crack your big teeth.

12:53.422 --> 12:55.253
Well, they're my big teeth.

12:55.758 --> 12:57.419
Yeah, some of them, some of them.

12:57.760 --> 12:59.751
I've got more teeth than you have.

13:00.095 --> 13:01.255
Two more.

13:03.766 --> 13:05.597
And you're going bald.

13:06.602 --> 13:07.432
So are you.

13:26.121 --> 13:27.110
Hello, honey.

13:30.793 --> 13:34.126
Come on and give your mommy
a big sloppy kiss.

13:35.631 --> 13:38.293
I want a big sloppy kiss!

13:38.634 --> 13:40.431
I don't want to kiss you right now.

13:42.805 --> 13:44.796
Where are these people you invited?

13:45.140 --> 13:49.804
Where is this good looking, well-built
young man and his slim-hipped wife?

13:50.813 --> 13:52.974
Talking to Daddy. They'll be here.

13:56.151 --> 13:57.641
Why didn't you want to kiss me?

14:11.000 --> 14:12.729
Why didn't you want to kiss me?

14:13.168 --> 14:17.161
If I kissed you I'd get all excited.
I'd get beside myself...

14:17.506 --> 14:20.839
...and then I'd have to take you by
force on the living room rug.

14:21.176 --> 14:25.670
Then our guests would walk in and
what would your father say about that?

14:26.181 --> 14:27.842
Oh, you pig!

14:30.185 --> 14:32.517
Fix me another drink, lover.

14:33.188 --> 14:35.486
God, you can swill it down, can't you?

14:35.691 --> 14:37.181
I'm thirsty!

14:37.526 --> 14:38.515
Oh, Jesus!

14:38.861 --> 14:42.854
I can drink you under any table you
want, so don't worry about me.

14:43.198 --> 14:47.862
You got the prize years ago.
You've won every abomination award.

14:49.038 --> 14:51.370
I swear if you existed I'd divorce you.

14:51.707 --> 14:54.835
- Stay on your feet for your guests.
- I can't even see you!

14:55.377 --> 14:59.370
If you pass out or throw up...
And try to keep your clothes on too.

14:59.715 --> 15:04.049
There's no more sickening sight than
you drunk and your skirt over your head.

15:04.887 --> 15:06.377
Your heads, I should say.

15:07.556 --> 15:09.717
Party! Party!

15:10.559 --> 15:12.754
I'm really looking forward to this.

15:12.962 --> 15:14.930
- Go answer the door.
- You answer it.

15:15.130 --> 15:16.392
Get to that door, you!

15:17.766 --> 15:18.698
Come on in!

15:18.901 --> 15:20.562
Get over and answer that door.

15:20.903 --> 15:25.067
All right. Whatever love wants.
Just don't start on the bit, that's all.

15:25.407 --> 15:26.965
The bit?

15:27.743 --> 15:30.576
What language is that?
Imitating one of your students?

15:30.913 --> 15:33.905
Don't start in on the bit
about the kid, that's all.

15:34.249 --> 15:36.547
- What do you take me for?
- Much too much.

15:36.752 --> 15:38.743
I'll start in on the kid if I want to.

15:39.088 --> 15:40.248
I'd advise against it.

15:40.589 --> 15:43.752
Well, good for you.
Get over there and open that door.

15:44.093 --> 15:45.253
You've been advised.

15:45.594 --> 15:46.583
Sure. Get over there.

15:46.929 --> 15:48.760
Yes, love. Whatever love wants.

15:49.598 --> 15:51.259
Some people still have manners...

15:51.600 --> 15:54.262
...and just don't break into
people's houses.

15:54.603 --> 15:58.266
Even if they hear a subhuman monster
yowling at them from inside.

15:58.607 --> 15:59.767
Goddamn you!

16:08.751 --> 16:10.719
You must be our little guests.

16:10.953 --> 16:14.514
Just ignore old sourpuss here.
Come on in, kids!

16:15.124 --> 16:17.957
Just hand your coats to old sourpuss
here.

16:18.460 --> 16:19.791
Perhaps we shouldn't have come.

16:20.129 --> 16:21.619
Yes, it is late!

16:21.964 --> 16:25.798
Late! Are you kidding?
Just throw your stuff down any place.

16:26.135 --> 16:28.968
Furniture, floor.
Makes no difference around here.

16:29.905 --> 16:31.600
I told you we shouldn't have come.

16:31.807 --> 16:33.968
I said come on in. Now come on!

16:36.812 --> 16:38.643
Look, muckmouth, you cut that out!

16:39.815 --> 16:41.976
Martha's a devil with language.

16:44.586 --> 16:46.019
Kids, sit down.

16:49.825 --> 16:51.986
Isn't this lovely?

16:54.163 --> 16:57.064
- Yes, indeed. Very handsome.
- Thank you.

17:12.314 --> 17:13.941
Who did the painting?

17:15.517 --> 17:19.009
Some Greek with a mustache
Martha attacked one night in a...

17:21.957 --> 17:24.016
It's got a...

17:24.526 --> 17:26.493
- Quiet intensity?
- Well, no...

17:26.694 --> 17:29.027
Then a certain
noisy relaxed quality maybe?

17:30.866 --> 17:33.027
How about a quietly
noisy relaxed intensity?

17:33.235 --> 17:35.032
Dear, you're being joshed.

17:35.704 --> 17:36.864
I'm aware of that.

17:37.206 --> 17:38.195
I am sorry.

17:38.540 --> 17:43.034
It's actually a pictorial representation
of the order of Martha's mind.

17:46.548 --> 17:47.674
Fix the kids a drink.

17:47.950 --> 17:49.747
What would you like to drink?

17:52.287 --> 17:53.584
What would you like?

17:54.723 --> 17:57.715
A little brandy maybe.
Never mix, never worry!

17:58.060 --> 18:00.221
Brandy? Just brandy.
Simple, simple.

18:00.562 --> 18:02.029
What about you...

18:05.901 --> 18:07.425
Bourbon, if you don't mind.

18:07.669 --> 18:10.069
Mind? I don't mind.
Don't think I mind.

18:10.405 --> 18:12.236
Martha, rubbing alcohol for you?

18:12.574 --> 18:14.565
Sure. Never mix, never worry!

18:24.920 --> 18:27.753
Who's afraid of Virginia Woolf?

18:30.259 --> 18:33.092
Wasn't that funny? That was so funny!

18:33.729 --> 18:34.559
Yes, it was.

18:34.763 --> 18:36.924
I thought I'd bust a gut!

18:40.102 --> 18:41.933
George didn't think it was funny.

18:42.271 --> 18:45.763
Martha thinks that unless you
bust a gut you're not amused.

18:46.108 --> 18:48.770
Unless you carry on like a hyena
you're not having fun.

18:49.111 --> 18:51.944
I certainly had fun.
It was a wonderful party!

18:52.214 --> 18:56.275
- It certainly was.
- Your father, he is so wonderful!

18:59.288 --> 19:01.449
He's quite a guy, isn't he?

19:01.790 --> 19:03.121
You better believe it.

19:03.458 --> 19:04.948
He's a marvelous man.

19:05.294 --> 19:07.455
I'm not tearing him down.
We know he's a god.

19:07.796 --> 19:09.127
You lay off my father.

19:09.464 --> 19:12.456
When you've had as many
faculty parties as I have...

19:12.801 --> 19:14.132
I rather appreciated it.

19:15.971 --> 19:18.804
I mean aside from enjoying it,
I appreciated it.

19:19.308 --> 19:23.802
Meeting, introducing, how he had us
stay at the Inn till our place is ready.

19:24.546 --> 19:25.774
When I taught in Kansas...

19:26.048 --> 19:27.447
You won't believe it...

19:27.649 --> 19:32.643
...but we had to make our way all by
ourselves. Isn't that right, dear?

19:32.988 --> 19:34.819
We had to make our own way.

19:35.023 --> 19:39.323
I'd have to go up to the wives
in the library or the supermarket...

19:39.661 --> 19:42.152
...and say, “Hello, I am new here.”

19:42.497 --> 19:45.989
“You must be Mrs. So-and-so,
Doctor So-and-so's wife.”

19:46.201 --> 19:48.499
It really wasn't very nice at all.

19:52.374 --> 19:53.864
Daddy knows how to run things.

19:54.710 --> 19:56.041
He's a remarkable man.

19:56.378 --> 19:57.709
You bet your sweet life.

19:58.714 --> 19:59.874
I'll tell you a secret.

20:00.549 --> 20:05.043
There are easier things in this world,
if you teach at the university...

20:05.387 --> 20:07.378
...than being married
to the daughter of...

20:07.723 --> 20:11.386
...the president of that university.
There are easier things.

20:11.727 --> 20:16.687
It's a great opportunity. For some men
it would be the chance of a lifetime.

20:16.899 --> 20:20.391
There are, believe me,
easier things in this world.

20:20.736 --> 20:23.398
Some men would give their right arm
for the chance!

20:23.739 --> 20:28.233
In reality that sacrifice is of a more
private portion of the anatomy.

20:30.579 --> 20:32.240
Could you show me where the...

20:32.748 --> 20:33.578
Are you all right?

20:33.916 --> 20:38.080
Of course, dear. I just want to
put some powder on my nose.

20:38.587 --> 20:40.748
Show her where we keep the euphemism?

20:44.927 --> 20:47.760
I'm sorry. I want to show you
the house anyway.

20:48.463 --> 20:49.896
We'll be back, dear.

20:51.099 --> 20:53.431
Honestly, George, you burn me up!

20:54.036 --> 20:55.003
You really do!

20:57.105 --> 20:59.437
Don't shoot your mouth off
about you-know-what.

21:00.108 --> 21:03.100
I'll talk about
any goddamn thing I want to!

21:03.445 --> 21:04.605
Okay, vanish!

21:04.947 --> 21:07.279
Any goddamn thing I want!

21:37.479 --> 21:38.707
What'll it be?

21:38.981 --> 21:40.471
I'll stick to bourbon.

21:47.990 --> 21:50.151
You're in the Math Department?

21:50.359 --> 21:51.223
No.

21:55.664 --> 21:57.996
Martha said so.
I think that's what she said.

22:05.007 --> 22:06.668
Why'd you decide to be a teacher?

22:08.343 --> 22:11.005
The same things that motivated you,
I imagine.

22:11.346 --> 22:12.677
Oh? What were they?

22:13.849 --> 22:15.840
What were the things that motivated me?

22:16.685 --> 22:18.175
Well, I'm sure I don't know.

22:18.387 --> 22:21.185
You said the things that motivated you
and me were the same.

22:21.523 --> 22:22.854
I said I imagined they were.

22:23.291 --> 22:24.451
Oh, did you?

22:35.904 --> 22:37.132
You like it here?

22:39.207 --> 22:40.367
Yes, it's fine.

22:40.709 --> 22:42.040
I meant the university.

22:43.745 --> 22:46.009
I know. I meant the university.

22:47.049 --> 22:48.880
Well, I like it fine.

23:02.230 --> 23:05.893
You've been here for quite a long time,
haven't you?

23:10.906 --> 23:15.070
Oh, yes. Ever since I married
what's-her-name. Martha.

23:16.244 --> 23:18.735
Even before that. Forever.

23:19.247 --> 23:21.078
Dashed hopes and good intentions.

23:22.084 --> 23:25.076
Good, better, best, bested!

23:27.255 --> 23:29.086
How do you like that for a declension?

23:29.591 --> 23:30.922
You didn't answer my question.

23:31.927 --> 23:36.421
Don't condescend. I asked you
how you liked that declension.

23:38.600 --> 23:39.965
I don't know what to say.

23:40.435 --> 23:41.766
You don't know what to say?

23:42.370 --> 23:45.771
Shall I say it's funny,
so you can say it's sad?

23:45.974 --> 23:50.775
Or shall I say it's sad so you can say
it's funny? You can play that game!

23:51.379 --> 23:53.279
- Very good!
- I think we'll just...

23:53.782 --> 23:56.273
Now, calm down. Just calm down.
All right?

23:56.618 --> 23:57.778
Another drink? Here.

23:58.120 --> 24:00.452
I still have one.
And when my wife comes down...

24:02.124 --> 24:06.788
What I mean is, you and your wife
seem to be having some sort of a...

24:07.462 --> 24:11.125
Martha and I are having nothing.
Martha and I are merely exercising.

24:11.466 --> 24:14.629
We're walking what's left of our wits.
Pay no attention.

24:14.970 --> 24:16.961
Now let's sit down and talk, huh?

24:17.639 --> 24:21.473
It's just I don't like to become
involved in other people's affairs.

24:21.977 --> 24:25.640
You'll get over that. Small college.
Musical beds is the faculty sport.

24:25.981 --> 24:26.811
Sir?

24:27.149 --> 24:29.982
Never mind. I wish you wouldn't go
“sir.” How old are you?

24:30.485 --> 24:31.474
Twenty-eight.

24:31.686 --> 24:32.983
I'm forty-something.

24:34.089 --> 24:36.489
Aren't you surprised?
Don't I look older?

24:38.994 --> 24:40.325
I think you look fine.

24:40.662 --> 24:43.995
I've always been lean. I play handball.
How much do you weigh?

24:45.500 --> 24:48.333
155, 160, something like that?
You play handball?

24:48.670 --> 24:50.535
- Not very well.
- We'll play sometime.

24:50.739 --> 24:55.176
Martha is 108... years old.
She weighs somewhat more than that.

24:55.510 --> 24:56.499
How old is your wife?

24:57.846 --> 24:59.177
She's twenty-six.

24:59.514 --> 25:03.006
Martha is a remarkable woman.
I imagine she weighs around 110.

25:03.351 --> 25:04.340
Your wife weighs...

25:04.686 --> 25:07.177
No, my boy, your wife.
My wife is Martha.

25:07.889 --> 25:09.151
Yes, I know.

25:09.691 --> 25:12.854
If you were married to Martha
you'd know what it means.

25:14.362 --> 25:16.853
If I were married to your wife,
I'd know what that means.

25:21.036 --> 25:24.199
Martha says you are in
the Math Department or something.

25:25.707 --> 25:26.696
No, I'm not.

25:27.042 --> 25:30.205
She's seldom mistaken.
Maybe you should be in it.

25:31.046 --> 25:33.640
I'm a biologist.
I'm in the Biology Department.

25:38.553 --> 25:42.887
You're the one's going to make all
that trouble making everyone the same.

25:43.225 --> 25:46.388
Rearranging the chromozones,
or whatever it is, right?

25:47.562 --> 25:49.393
Not exactly. Chromosomes.

25:49.898 --> 25:51.058
I'm very mistrustful.

25:52.400 --> 25:55.892
You think we learn nothing from history?
I'm in the History Department.

25:56.638 --> 25:57.536
Yes, I know.

25:57.739 --> 26:00.230
Martha tells me I'm in
the History Department...

26:00.575 --> 26:05.069
...as opposed to being the History
Department, in the sense of running it.

26:05.413 --> 26:08.246
I do not run the History Department.

26:08.583 --> 26:10.414
I don't run the Biology Department.

26:10.619 --> 26:12.246
You're twenty-one. Twenty-eight.

26:12.754 --> 26:16.747
Perhaps when you're forty-something
you'll run the History Department.

26:17.592 --> 26:18.923
Biology Department.

26:19.427 --> 26:21.918
I'm really very mistrustful!

26:22.764 --> 26:26.757
I read somewhere that science fiction
is not really fiction at all.

26:27.102 --> 26:31.198
That you rearrange my genes so that
everyone will be like everyone else.

26:31.606 --> 26:34.439
I suspect we shall not have
much music or painting.

26:35.143 --> 26:39.443
But we'll have a civilization of
sublime young men much like yourself.

26:39.781 --> 26:43.945
Cultures and races will vanish.
The ants will take over the world.

26:44.619 --> 26:46.450
Don't know much about science, do you?

26:46.788 --> 26:49.621
I know history.
I know when I'm being threatened.

26:51.793 --> 26:53.954
Your wife doesn't have any hips,
does she?

26:55.964 --> 27:00.298
I'm not hip-happy. I was implying
that your wife is slim-hipped.

27:01.636 --> 27:02.864
Yes, she is.

27:03.471 --> 27:04.460
You got any kids?

27:05.140 --> 27:06.971
No. Not yet. You?

27:07.309 --> 27:08.799
For me to know and you to find out.

27:12.147 --> 27:13.546
No kids, huh?

27:14.449 --> 27:15.143
What's wrong?

27:15.950 --> 27:18.783
Nothing. We wanted to wait
till we're settled.

27:22.324 --> 27:23.985
Think you'll be happy
here at New Carthage?

27:24.659 --> 27:27.992
Well, we hope to stay here.
I don't mean forever.

27:28.496 --> 27:31.659
Don't bandy that about.
The Old Man wouldn't like it.

27:33.335 --> 27:37.499
Martha's father expects his staff
to come here and grow old...

27:37.839 --> 27:40.239
...and fall in the line of service.

27:40.442 --> 27:42.672
One man, a professor of Latin...

27:43.011 --> 27:45.673
...actually fell in the
cafeteria line one lunch.

27:46.014 --> 27:49.506
But the Old Man isn't falling anywhere.
He isn't going to die.

27:50.352 --> 27:51.683
There are rumors...

27:52.020 --> 27:55.683
...which you can't breathe to Martha
for she foams at the mouth...

27:56.191 --> 27:57.681
...that the Old Man, her father...

27:58.026 --> 28:01.189
...is over two hundred years old.

28:01.696 --> 28:04.859
There's an irony there, but I'm not
drunk enough to figure it out.

28:08.536 --> 28:09.525
Damnit!

28:10.205 --> 28:13.538
I wonder what women talk about
when men talk. I must find out.

28:14.209 --> 28:15.870
What do you want?

28:18.213 --> 28:20.044
Isn't that a wonderful sound?

28:20.882 --> 28:22.247
How many kids you having?

28:23.218 --> 28:24.879
I don't know. My wife is...

28:25.220 --> 28:28.053
Slim-hipped.
Well, there's one of you at least.

28:28.390 --> 28:33.054
You must see this house, dear.
This is such a wonderful old house.

28:34.562 --> 28:36.826
For Christ's sake, hang on a minute!

28:37.031 --> 28:38.896
She'll be right down, she's changing.

28:39.234 --> 28:41.225
She's changing? What, her clothes?

28:41.469 --> 28:42.800
- Her dress.
- Why?

28:43.004 --> 28:45.871
I imagine that she wants
to be comfortable.

28:46.074 --> 28:47.735
Oh, she does, does she?

28:48.009 --> 28:49.567
You don't know!

28:51.646 --> 28:54.581
- You all right, dear?
- Yes, dear, perfectly fine.

28:55.250 --> 28:56.740
She wants to be comfortable?

28:57.419 --> 28:58.750
Well, we'll see about that!

28:59.254 --> 29:01.051
I didn't know that you had a son.

29:04.259 --> 29:07.251
- A son. I hadn't known.
- You to know and me to find out, huh?

29:07.595 --> 29:10.257
Tomorrow is his birthday.
He will be sixteen.

29:11.833 --> 29:12.765
She told you?

29:13.868 --> 29:15.495
- She told you about him?
- Yes.

29:16.771 --> 29:18.295
You said she's changing?

29:19.307 --> 29:21.275
- And she mentioned...
- Your son's birthday.

29:26.114 --> 29:27.604
You look pale. Would you like...

29:27.949 --> 29:31.441
Yes, dear a little more brandy maybe.
Just a drop.

29:32.320 --> 29:33.446
The bar?

29:33.922 --> 29:37.790
Yes, by all means, drink away.
You'll need it as years go on.

29:39.294 --> 29:41.125
Damn destructive...

29:41.463 --> 29:42.953
What time is it, dear?

29:44.332 --> 29:46.493
- 2:30.
- So late!

29:46.801 --> 29:47.961
We should get home.

29:48.470 --> 29:49.994
Keeping the baby sitter up?

29:51.806 --> 29:53.296
I said we didn't have children.

29:54.142 --> 29:56.133
Sorry, I wasn't even listening.

29:56.478 --> 29:58.309
Or thinking. Whichever applies.

29:59.147 --> 30:00.273
We'll go in a while.

30:00.648 --> 30:02.138
No, you mustn't!

30:02.550 --> 30:07.647
Martha is changing, and not for me.
Martha hasn't changed for me in years.

30:07.989 --> 30:11.982
It means we're going to be here days.
You're being accorded an honor.

30:12.327 --> 30:16.491
Don't forget Martha is the daughter
of our beloved boss... his right arm.

30:17.165 --> 30:19.827
I'd use another word,
but leave that sort of talk to Martha.

30:20.335 --> 30:21.632
What sort of talk?

30:25.840 --> 30:26.829
Well, now!

30:29.143 --> 30:31.304
Why, Martha, your Sunday chapel dress!

30:31.646 --> 30:33.978
Oh, that's most attractive!

30:34.315 --> 30:35.646
You like it? Good.

30:37.051 --> 30:39.645
What do you mean screaming
up the stairs at me?

30:39.854 --> 30:42.982
We got lonely for the soft purr
of your little voice.

30:43.658 --> 30:46.491
Well, you just trot over
to the bar-ie-poo...

30:46.828 --> 30:49.820
...and make your little mommy
a great big drink.

30:50.164 --> 30:51.324
That's right!

30:54.769 --> 30:59.172
You're quite a guy, getting your masters
when you were what, 12?

31:00.008 --> 31:02.499
- Hear that, George?
- 12 and a half, actually.

31:03.344 --> 31:04.311
19, really.

31:04.546 --> 31:07.447
- You needn't have mentioned it.
- I'm proud of you!

31:07.649 --> 31:09.913
- I'm very impressed.
- You're damn right!

31:10.118 --> 31:14.020
I'm wracked with jealousy.
What do you want me to do, throw up?

31:15.390 --> 31:18.018
That's very impressive.
You should be proud.

31:18.359 --> 31:20.350
He's a pretty nice fellow.

31:21.029 --> 31:23.190
You might take over
the History Department.

31:23.398 --> 31:24.695
Biology Department.

31:25.366 --> 31:27.027
Yes. I'm preoccupied with history.

31:29.037 --> 31:31.870
What a remark.
“I am preoccupied with history.”

31:34.375 --> 31:38.368
George is not. George is preoccupied
with the History Department.

31:38.880 --> 31:40.871
He's preoccupied with it...

31:41.215 --> 31:45.379
...because he is not the
History Department, he is only in it.

31:45.720 --> 31:48.211
We went through that
while you were upstairs.

31:48.556 --> 31:50.387
That's right, baby, keep it clean.

31:51.225 --> 31:54.058
George is bogged down
in the History Department.

31:55.229 --> 31:57.720
He's an old bog
in the History Department.

31:58.199 --> 31:59.757
That's what George is...

31:59.968 --> 32:03.927
...A bog, a fen, a G.D. Swamp!

32:07.408 --> 32:09.899
Hey, swamp! Hey, swampy!

32:14.916 --> 32:16.076
Can I get you something?

32:18.252 --> 32:19.082
Well, sure.

32:19.554 --> 32:23.251
You can light my cigarette
if you're of a mind to.

32:23.591 --> 32:25.582
No. There are limits.

32:26.427 --> 32:27.917
A man puts up with only so much...

32:28.262 --> 32:31.925
...before he descends on the
evolutionary ladder which is your line.

32:32.767 --> 32:36.601
I'll hold your hand when it's dark
and you're afraid of the bogeyman.

32:36.938 --> 32:39.930
And I'll tote your gin bottles
out after midnight so no one sees.

32:40.274 --> 32:44.608
But I will not light your cigarette.
And that, as they say, is that.

32:50.752 --> 32:52.947
Hey, you played football, huh?

32:53.287 --> 32:55.118
Yes, I was a quarterback.

32:55.356 --> 32:57.790
But I was much more adept at boxing.

32:58.626 --> 33:01.288
Boxing? You hear that, George?

33:02.797 --> 33:05.891
Must've been good. Doesn't look
like you got hit in the face.

33:06.300 --> 33:09.133
He was intercollegiate state
middleweight champion.

33:10.972 --> 33:14.135
Still looks like you have a
pretty good body, is that right?

33:14.342 --> 33:15.707
Decency forbids...

33:15.910 --> 33:17.138
Shut up!

33:17.645 --> 33:20.637
Is that right?
Have you kept your body up?

33:21.149 --> 33:23.640
It's still pretty good. I work out.

33:25.353 --> 33:27.981
Yes, he has a very firm body.

33:28.489 --> 33:30.957
Have you? I think that's very nice.

33:31.325 --> 33:33.987
You know, once you have it,
you never know...

33:34.328 --> 33:35.818
...when it'll come in handy!

33:38.499 --> 33:40.967
I say, why give it up until you have to?

33:44.772 --> 33:46.933
I couldn't agree with you more!

33:47.341 --> 33:49.002
Your obscenity is beyond human...

33:49.343 --> 33:52.176
George here doesn't cotton
too much to body talk.

33:52.413 --> 33:57.373
Paunchy isn't happy when the talk
moves to muscles. How much you weigh?

33:59.253 --> 34:00.686
155, 150...

34:01.856 --> 34:04.848
Still at the old middleweight limit?
That's pretty good!

34:08.730 --> 34:11.062
Tell them about the boxing match we had.

34:12.867 --> 34:13.697
Christ!

34:15.369 --> 34:16.666
Tell them about it.

34:16.938 --> 34:18.996
You tell them, you're good at it.

34:19.474 --> 34:22.204
- Is he all right?
- Him? Oh, sure.

34:23.210 --> 34:24.940
We had this boxing match...

34:25.213 --> 34:27.204
...a couple years after we married.

34:27.547 --> 34:29.539
A boxing match? The two of you?

34:30.717 --> 34:32.708
Yeah, the two of us. Really.

34:33.721 --> 34:35.210
I can't imagine it!

34:35.556 --> 34:38.217
Well, it wasn't in a ring
or anything like that.

34:38.893 --> 34:41.225
Daddy was on this physical fitness kick.

34:41.896 --> 34:45.559
He had a couple of us over one Sunday
and we all went out back...

34:45.900 --> 34:50.063
...and Daddy put the gloves on himself
and asked George to box with him.

34:51.906 --> 34:53.897
And George didn't want to.

34:54.641 --> 34:59.602
So Daddy said, “Come on, young man!
What sort of a son-in-law are you? “

35:01.249 --> 35:05.083
And while this was going on,
I don't know why I did it...

35:05.419 --> 35:07.887
...I got into a pair of gloves myself...

35:08.089 --> 35:12.583
...and I snuck up behind George,
just kidding and yelled, “Hey, George! “

35:13.261 --> 35:17.254
And let go with a sort of roundhouse
right. Just kidding, you know.

35:18.099 --> 35:22.661
And George wheeled around real quick
and caught it right in the jaw!

35:25.807 --> 35:28.332
He caught it right in the jaw!

35:29.443 --> 35:33.812
He was off-balance. He must have been.
And then he landed...

35:34.048 --> 35:36.608
...flat in a huckleberry bush!

35:59.574 --> 36:00.541
Pow, you're dead.

36:07.315 --> 36:09.306
Where'd you get that, you bastard?

36:09.650 --> 36:12.312
I've had it awhile. Liked that, did
you?

36:12.653 --> 36:13.642
Bastard!

36:16.324 --> 36:19.316
Oh, that was pretty good.
Hey, give me a kiss.

36:19.660 --> 36:22.151
- Later, sweetie.
- Give me a kiss.

36:26.934 --> 36:30.335
So that's what you're after?
We having blue games for the guests?

36:30.671 --> 36:34.004
Everything in its place.
Everything in it's own good time.

36:34.842 --> 36:36.833
Drinks now. Drinks for all.

36:37.178 --> 36:39.169
You've nibbled away at your glass.

36:40.014 --> 36:43.347
I need something.
I was never so frightened in my life.

36:43.684 --> 36:45.276
Weren't you frightened?

36:46.854 --> 36:49.448
- I don't remember.
- I bet you were.

36:49.690 --> 36:51.521
Did you think I was going to kill you?

36:51.826 --> 36:54.351
You? Kill me? That's a laugh!

36:54.695 --> 36:55.855
I might some day.

36:57.365 --> 36:58.559
Fat chance!

36:58.799 --> 37:00.130
Where's the john?

37:01.202 --> 37:02.362
Down the hall and right.

37:02.703 --> 37:05.194
Don't come back with
any guns or anything.

37:06.040 --> 37:08.201
You don't need any props,
do you, baby?

37:08.709 --> 37:10.108
I'll bet not.

37:10.311 --> 37:13.712
- No fake gun for you!
- May I leave my drink here?

37:14.081 --> 37:17.608
Why not? We've got half-filled glasses
wherever Martha left them.

37:17.852 --> 37:20.878
In the closet, the bathtub.
I found one in the freezer.

37:21.088 --> 37:24.057
- Oh, you did not!
- Yes, I did.

37:26.894 --> 37:29.454
- Brandy gives you no hangover?
- I never mix.

37:29.664 --> 37:32.997
- I don't drink very much either.
- Oh, good.

37:34.068 --> 37:36.559
Your husband was telling us
about chromosomes.

37:37.571 --> 37:40.870
- Chromosomes. He's a biologist.
- He's in the Math Department.

37:41.075 --> 37:43.566
- Biologist.
- He's in the Math Department!

37:45.613 --> 37:46.739
Biology.

37:48.416 --> 37:49.747
Are you sure?

37:50.084 --> 37:52.245
Well, I ought to be sure.

37:53.754 --> 37:56.416
So he's a biologist. Good for him!

37:57.425 --> 37:59.086
Biology's even better.

37:59.760 --> 38:02.752
It's at the meat of things.
You're at the meat of things.

38:03.297 --> 38:07.097
- She thought you were Math Department.
- Maybe I ought to be.

38:07.435 --> 38:11.098
You stay right where you are.
Stay right at the meat of things.

38:11.739 --> 38:14.264
You're obsessed by that phrase.
It's ugly.

38:14.608 --> 38:15.939
You stay right there.

38:17.111 --> 38:21.104
You can take over the History Department
as easy from there as any place else.

38:21.782 --> 38:25.115
Somebody's got to take over
the History Department some day.

38:25.453 --> 38:28.786
And it ain't gonna be Georgie-boy
over there, that's for sure.

38:29.123 --> 38:31.648
Are you swampy, are you?

38:32.460 --> 38:35.452
In my mind you are bedded in cement
up to the neck.

38:36.130 --> 38:37.722
No, up to the nose, it's quieter.

38:45.006 --> 38:46.132
When is your son...

38:47.341 --> 38:47.932
What?

38:48.275 --> 38:49.640
Something about your son.

38:54.849 --> 38:56.817
When is your son coming home?

39:04.325 --> 39:05.656
When's our son coming home?

39:05.993 --> 39:06.823
Never mind.

39:07.161 --> 39:10.494
I want to know. You brought it up.
When's he coming home?

39:11.499 --> 39:14.195
I said never mind.
I'm sorry I brought it up.

39:14.468 --> 39:17.835
Him up! Not it! You brought him up,
more or less.

39:18.339 --> 39:21.672
When's the little bugger appearing?
Isn't tomorrow his birthday?

39:22.009 --> 39:23.840
I don't want to talk about it.

39:24.512 --> 39:26.537
I don't want to talk about it!

39:26.747 --> 39:29.181
She doesn't want to talk about it, him.

39:29.383 --> 39:32.250
Martha is sorry she brought it up. Him.

39:32.520 --> 39:34.852
When's the little bugger coming home?

39:36.724 --> 39:40.854
Since you had the bad taste to
bring it up, when is the bugger coming?

39:41.362 --> 39:44.525
George talks disparagingly about
the little bugger...

39:44.865 --> 39:46.890
...because he has problems.

39:47.101 --> 39:49.262
What problems has the little bugger got?

39:49.470 --> 39:52.200
Not the little bugger.
Stop calling him that!

39:52.540 --> 39:57.307
- You! You've got problems!
- Never heard anything more ridiculous.

39:57.878 --> 39:59.368
Neither have I!

40:00.881 --> 40:04.044
George's biggest problem
about the... about our son...

40:04.385 --> 40:08.219
...about our great big son is that deep
down in the private pit of his gut...

40:08.556 --> 40:11.719
...he is not completely sure that it's
his own kid.

40:12.059 --> 40:14.027
My God, you're a wicked woman!

40:14.228 --> 40:18.562
And I've told you a million times,
I wouldn't conceive with anyone else.

40:18.899 --> 40:20.764
A deeply wicked person.

40:22.169 --> 40:24.330
I'm not sure this is a subject for...

40:24.605 --> 40:28.405
Martha's lying. I want you
to know that Martha is lying.

40:29.243 --> 40:32.076
There are few things I am certain of,
but the one thing...

40:32.279 --> 40:34.839
...in this sinking world
that I am sure of...

40:35.049 --> 40:38.246
...is my partnership,
my chromosomoligical partnership...

40:38.452 --> 40:42.650
...in the creation of our blond-eyed,
blue-haired son.

40:43.724 --> 40:45.089
I'm so glad.

40:46.193 --> 40:49.287
- A very pretty speech, George.
- Thank you, Martha.

40:49.530 --> 40:52.863
You rose to the occasion good.
Real good.

40:53.200 --> 40:54.531
Well. Real well!

40:56.270 --> 40:57.635
Martha knows better.

40:57.905 --> 41:00.703
Yes, I've been to college
like everybody else.

41:01.041 --> 41:04.533
George, our son does not
have blue hair.

41:04.879 --> 41:08.212
Or blue eyes for that matter.
He has green eyes like me.

41:08.549 --> 41:10.881
Beautiful, beautiful green eyes.

41:11.552 --> 41:12.541
He has blue eyes.

41:12.887 --> 41:13.581
Green.

41:14.054 --> 41:14.884
Blue, Martha.

41:15.222 --> 41:16.587
Green, you bastard!

41:17.591 --> 41:19.889
Tut-tut yourself, you old floozy.

41:20.194 --> 41:21.889
He's not a floozie.

41:22.730 --> 41:25.460
He can't be a floozie.
You're a floozie.

41:25.733 --> 41:27.598
Now you just watch yourself!

41:28.068 --> 41:29.399
All right!

41:30.070 --> 41:33.301
I'd like another little nipper
of brandy please.

41:33.574 --> 41:35.508
- I think you've had enough.
- Nonsense!

41:35.743 --> 41:38.337
- We're all ready, I think.
- Nonsense!

41:41.048 --> 41:45.075
George has watery blue eyes,
kind of milky blue.

41:45.286 --> 41:46.617
Make up your mind.

41:46.820 --> 41:50.551
I gave you the benefit of a doubt.
Daddy has green eyes too.

41:50.758 --> 41:55.252
No, he has tiny red eyes, like a white
mouse. In fact, he is a white mouse.

41:56.430 --> 41:59.422
You wouldn't say that if he was here.
You're a coward!

41:59.767 --> 42:03.100
You know that shock of white hair
and these beady red eyes?

42:03.437 --> 42:05.098
A great big white mouse.

42:05.773 --> 42:10.437
George hates Daddy. Not for anything
Daddy's done to him, but for his own...

42:10.778 --> 42:11.938
Inadequacies?

42:12.279 --> 42:15.271
That's right.
You hit it right on the snout!

42:15.783 --> 42:18.445
You know why the S.O.B.
Hates my father?

42:18.786 --> 42:22.119
When George came to the History
Department, about 500 years ago...

42:22.456 --> 42:23.616
...Daddy approved of him.

42:24.124 --> 42:28.117
And you want to know what I did,
dumb cluck that I am?

42:28.462 --> 42:30.327
I fell for him!

42:30.731 --> 42:32.130
I like that!

42:32.466 --> 42:34.434
She did, you should have seen it.

42:34.635 --> 42:38.127
She'd sit outside my room at night
and howl and claw at the turf.

42:38.439 --> 42:40.270
I couldn't work so I married her.

42:42.643 --> 42:44.474
I actually fell for him.

42:44.979 --> 42:46.810
It! That! There!

42:47.147 --> 42:48.637
Martha's a romantic at heart.

42:50.317 --> 42:51.477
That I am.

42:53.320 --> 42:57.654
I actually fell for him.
And the match seemed practical too.

42:58.492 --> 43:01.325
For a while Daddy thought
George had the stuff...

43:01.662 --> 43:03.823
...to take over when
he was ready to retire.

43:05.332 --> 43:07.027
- Stop it!
- What do you want?!

43:07.501 --> 43:10.299
- I wouldn't go on if I were you.
- You wouldn't? Well, you're not!

43:10.504 --> 43:13.200
You've already sprung a leak
about you-know-what.

43:13.741 --> 43:14.366
What?

43:14.675 --> 43:16.836
About the little bugger. Our son.

43:17.177 --> 43:19.168
If you start in on this, I warn you...

43:19.513 --> 43:22.380
- I stand warned.
- Do we have to go through this?

43:22.850 --> 43:26.047
Anyway, I married the S.O.B.
I had it all planned out.

43:26.253 --> 43:30.519
First he'd take over the History
Department, then the whole college.

43:30.858 --> 43:32.519
That's how it was supposed to be!

43:32.860 --> 43:33.849
Getting angry?

43:34.194 --> 43:37.357
That was how it was supposed to be.
All very simple.

43:37.698 --> 43:40.531
Daddy thought it was a good idea too.
For a while!

43:40.868 --> 43:43.530
Until he started watching
for a couple of years.

43:43.871 --> 43:44.860
Getting angry?

43:45.205 --> 43:47.196
Till he watched for a couple years...

43:47.541 --> 43:50.203
...and started thinking
it wasn't such a good idea.

43:50.544 --> 43:53.536
That maybe Georgie-boy
didn't have the stuff!

43:54.014 --> 43:55.743
That he didn't have it in him!

43:55.949 --> 43:58.383
- Stop it, Martha!
- Like hell, I will!

43:59.453 --> 44:02.547
George didn't have much push.
He wasn't aggressive.

44:03.390 --> 44:05.381
In fact, he was sort of a flop!

44:06.060 --> 44:08.221
A great big, fat flop!

44:09.263 --> 44:10.730
I said stop it!

44:11.065 --> 44:15.399
I hope that was an empty bottle.
You can't afford to waste good liquor.

44:15.736 --> 44:19.570
Not on your salary! Not on
an associate professor's salary!

44:20.407 --> 44:23.570
So here I am, stuck with this flop...

44:23.911 --> 44:26.243
...this bog in the History Department.

44:26.580 --> 44:29.071
Who's married
to the president's daughter...

44:29.416 --> 44:33.409
...who's expected to be somebody.
Not just a nobody!

44:33.754 --> 44:37.417
A bookworm who's so
goddamn complacent...

44:37.758 --> 44:40.090
...he can't make anything
out of himself.

44:40.427 --> 44:43.760
That doesn't have the guts
to make anybody proud of him!

44:46.600 --> 44:48.431
All right, George, stop it!

44:50.804 --> 44:52.499
I'm going to be sick!

45:25.172 --> 45:27.640
She'll be all right.
I'll make some coffee.

45:28.475 --> 45:31.205
- You sure?
- She'll be okay.

47:38.939 --> 47:40.600
I'm really very sorry.

47:44.111 --> 47:47.103
She really shouldn't drink.
She's frail.

47:50.617 --> 47:52.107
Slim-hipped, as you say.

47:55.622 --> 47:58.955
Where's my little yum-yum?
Where's Martha?

48:00.794 --> 48:03.661
I think she's going to make some coffee.

48:08.969 --> 48:10.766
She gets sick quite easily.

48:11.305 --> 48:14.297
Martha? No, she hasn't been
sick a day in her life.

48:14.641 --> 48:16.973
Unless you count time
she spends in the rest home.

48:17.311 --> 48:18.801
No, no. My wife.

48:19.146 --> 48:23.310
My wife gets sick quite easily.
Your wife is Martha.

48:26.820 --> 48:27.650
I know.

48:29.323 --> 48:31.814
She doesn't really spend any time
in a rest home?

48:33.327 --> 48:34.316
Your wife?

48:34.995 --> 48:35.984
No, yours.

48:37.331 --> 48:38.161
Mine?

48:44.004 --> 48:46.165
She doesn't. I would.

48:49.810 --> 48:52.506
If I were her... she... I would.

48:52.846 --> 48:55.178
But then I'm not and so I don't.

48:57.684 --> 48:59.311
I'd like to, though.

49:01.021 --> 49:03.854
It gets pretty bouncy
around here sometimes.

49:05.359 --> 49:06.519
Yes, I'm sure.

49:10.764 --> 49:13.426
- Your wife throws up a lot?
- I didn't say that.

49:13.800 --> 49:16.030
I said she gets sick quite easily.

49:17.237 --> 49:18.864
By sick I thought that you meant she...

49:19.373 --> 49:22.399
It's true, actually.
She does throw up a lot.

49:22.609 --> 49:23.701
The word is often.

49:25.245 --> 49:27.873
Once she starts
there's practically no stopping.

49:29.883 --> 49:31.942
She'll go right on for hours.

49:34.955 --> 49:36.582
Not all the time.

49:38.825 --> 49:39.883
Regularly.

49:40.727 --> 49:42.991
- You can tell time by her?
- Just about.

49:55.909 --> 49:57.809
I married her because she was pregnant.

50:02.716 --> 50:05.014
But you said you didn't have
any children.

50:05.218 --> 50:06.708
She wasn't really. It was a...

50:08.889 --> 50:10.220
...hysterical pregnancy.

50:12.392 --> 50:15.555
She blew up and then she went down.

50:17.097 --> 50:19.292
And when she was up you married her?

50:21.068 --> 50:22.797
Then she went down.

50:45.659 --> 50:47.559
When I was 16...

50:48.829 --> 50:51.423
...and going to prep school,
during the Punic Wars...

50:54.034 --> 50:56.935
...a bunch of us would go to town
the first day of vacation...

50:57.270 --> 50:59.261
...before we fanned out to our homes.

51:01.708 --> 51:04.836
And in the evening
we would go to a gin mill...

51:05.112 --> 51:07.774
...owned by the gangster-father
of one of us...

51:08.115 --> 51:12.108
...and we would drink with the grown-ups
and listen to the jazz.

51:13.954 --> 51:15.785
And one time, in the bunch of us...

51:16.123 --> 51:17.681
...there was this...

51:18.225 --> 51:20.819
...boy who was 15...

51:21.628 --> 51:25.792
...and he had killed his mother
with a shotgun some years before.

51:27.134 --> 51:29.125
Completely accidentally...

51:29.469 --> 51:33.132
...without even an unconscious
motivation, I have no doubt at all.

51:35.242 --> 51:37.802
And this one time this boy
went with us and...

51:38.645 --> 51:40.840
...we ordered our drinks...

51:41.748 --> 51:44.012
...and when it came his turn he said...

51:44.684 --> 51:46.652
“I'll have bergin.

51:47.354 --> 51:51.814
“Give me some bergin please.
Bergin and water.”

51:54.928 --> 51:56.452
We all laughed.

51:57.430 --> 52:02.458
He was blond and he had the face
of a cherub, and we all laughed.

52:03.637 --> 52:07.129
And his cheeks went red
and the color rose in his neck.

52:07.674 --> 52:12.611
The waiter told people at the next table
what the boy said and they laughed...

52:13.013 --> 52:17.507
...and then more people were told
and the laughter grew and grew.

52:22.756 --> 52:25.418
No one was laughing more than us...

52:25.759 --> 52:29.593
...and none of us more than the boy
who had shot his mother.

52:32.098 --> 52:36.262
And soon everyone in the gin mill
knew what the laughter was about...

52:36.603 --> 52:41.267
...and everyone started ordering bergin
and laughing when they ordered it.

52:42.442 --> 52:45.434
And soon, of course,
the laughter became less general...

52:45.779 --> 52:50.113
...but it did not subside entirely
for a very long time.

52:50.450 --> 52:53.442
For always at this table or that...

52:53.954 --> 52:55.945
...someone would order bergin...

52:56.990 --> 53:00.790
...and a whole new area
of laughter would rise.

53:02.629 --> 53:04.119
We drank free that night.

53:05.398 --> 53:07.628
We were bought champagne
by the management...

53:07.968 --> 53:11.131
...by the gangster-father of one of us.

53:13.306 --> 53:16.969
And, of course,
we suffered the next day...

53:17.310 --> 53:21.644
...each of us alone,
on his train away from the city...

53:23.383 --> 53:27.149
...and each of us
with a grown-up's hangover.

53:29.656 --> 53:31.749
But it was the grandest day...

53:33.159 --> 53:34.490
...of my...

53:36.029 --> 53:37.360
...youth.

53:49.476 --> 53:50.807
What happened to the boy?

53:53.880 --> 53:55.370
The boy who had shot his mother.

53:58.218 --> 53:59.207
I won't tell you.

54:02.422 --> 54:06.051
The next summer on a country road,
with his learner's permit...

54:06.259 --> 54:10.958
...and his father sitting to his right,
he swerved to avoid a porcupine...

54:12.065 --> 54:14.898
...and drove straight into a large tree.

54:17.170 --> 54:18.728
He was not killed, of course.

54:19.906 --> 54:23.398
In the hospital when he was conscious
and out of danger...

54:23.743 --> 54:26.234
...when they told him
his father was dead...

54:27.914 --> 54:30.906
...he began to laugh, I have been told.

54:32.252 --> 54:35.915
And his laughter grew
and would not stop.

54:37.924 --> 54:41.587
And it was not until after
they'd jammed a needle in his arm...

54:41.928 --> 54:46.262
...not until his consciousness
had slipped away from him...

54:46.599 --> 54:50.262
...that his laughter subsided. Stopped.

54:52.439 --> 54:54.771
When he recovered
from his injuries enough...

54:55.108 --> 54:59.772
...so he could be moved without damage
should he struggle...

55:02.115 --> 55:04.140
...he was put in an asylum.

55:07.454 --> 55:09.115
That was thirty years ago.

55:10.790 --> 55:12.451
Is he still there?

55:14.461 --> 55:15.519
Oh, yes.

55:16.963 --> 55:19.124
I'm told that for these thirty years...

55:21.001 --> 55:22.798
...he has not uttered...

55:24.471 --> 55:27.133
...one sound.

55:49.362 --> 55:50.659
That's Big Martha.

55:51.531 --> 55:52.998
She's making coffee.

55:54.334 --> 55:57.997
For your hysterical wife,
who goes up and down.

55:59.005 --> 55:59.733
Went.

56:00.340 --> 56:01.864
Up and down.

56:02.342 --> 56:04.333
Went? And no more?

56:05.345 --> 56:07.506
No more. Nothing.

56:10.016 --> 56:12.746
Martha doesn't have
hysterical pregnancies.

56:13.520 --> 56:15.454
My wife had one.

56:15.688 --> 56:18.179
Martha doesn't have pregnancies at all.

56:21.861 --> 56:25.297
Do you have any other kids,
any daughters or anything?

56:26.866 --> 56:28.697
Do we have any what?

56:32.038 --> 56:34.165
I mean, do you only have
the one...

56:34.941 --> 56:36.533
...kid, your son?

56:38.711 --> 56:40.201
No, just one.

56:41.881 --> 56:43.109
One boy.

56:44.551 --> 56:45.916
Our son.

56:51.157 --> 56:52.419
That's nice.

56:55.061 --> 56:57.052
He's a comfort.

56:58.898 --> 57:00.229
He's a beanbag.

57:03.369 --> 57:04.336
A what?

57:04.571 --> 57:06.402
A beanbag. You wouldn't understand.

57:08.741 --> 57:10.470
A beanbag!

57:10.677 --> 57:14.204
I heard! I didn't say I was deaf,
I said I didn't understand!

57:14.414 --> 57:19.215
- You didn't say that at all.
- I was implying I didn't understand.

57:21.254 --> 57:22.721
- You're getting testy.
- I'm sorry!

57:22.922 --> 57:27.256
I just said our son, the apple of
our 3 eyes, Martha being a Cyclops...

57:27.760 --> 57:29.921
...our son is a beanbag,
and you get testy.

57:30.263 --> 57:33.562
It's late, I'm tired.
I've been drinking since 9 o'clock.

57:33.766 --> 57:37.167
My wife is vomiting.
There's been a lot of screaming here.

57:37.370 --> 57:39.634
You get testy, naturally.
Don't worry about it.

57:39.839 --> 57:43.002
Anybody coming here gets testy.
Don't be upset.

57:43.209 --> 57:45.404
- I'm not upset.
- You're testy.

57:49.949 --> 57:53.942
I'd like to set you straight
about something while we're out here.

57:54.787 --> 57:56.948
About something Martha said.

57:58.291 --> 58:00.282
Hark! Forest sounds.

58:01.294 --> 58:02.625
Animal noises.

58:05.198 --> 58:07.132
Oh, well, here's nursie!

58:08.134 --> 58:10.466
We're sitting up, we're having coffee.

58:12.138 --> 58:14.129
Is there anything I should do?

58:14.474 --> 58:18.808
No, you just stay there
and listen to Georgie's side of things.

58:19.312 --> 58:20.973
Bore yourself to death!

58:21.247 --> 58:23.807
You clean up the mess you made in here?

58:24.150 --> 58:27.142
No, Martha, I did not
clean up the mess I made.

58:28.521 --> 58:32.287
I've been trying for years
to clean up the mess I made.

58:32.659 --> 58:34.354
Have you been trying for years?

58:34.561 --> 58:36.654
Accommodation, adjustment...

58:37.163 --> 58:39.654
...those do seem to be
in the order of things.

58:39.866 --> 58:41.663
Don't put me in the same class with you.

58:42.001 --> 58:45.493
No, of course not.
I mean things are simpler for you.

58:46.639 --> 58:49.130
You marry a woman
because she's all blown up.

58:49.342 --> 58:54.109
- Where I, in my old-fashioned way...
- There was more to it than that.

58:54.314 --> 58:56.305
Sure. I bet she has money too.

58:59.519 --> 59:00.144
Yes.

59:06.526 --> 59:08.187
You mean I was right? I hit it?

59:08.861 --> 59:12.729
My God, what archery! First try, too.
How about that?

59:13.366 --> 59:15.357
- There were other things.
- Yes.

59:15.568 --> 59:17.195
To compensate.

59:18.037 --> 59:19.902
There always are.

59:21.474 --> 59:22.236
Allow me.

59:25.044 --> 59:28.036
Tell me about your wife's money.

59:31.284 --> 59:32.216
No.

59:32.719 --> 59:34.118
Okay, don't.

59:38.191 --> 59:40.921
My father-in-law was a man of the Lord.

59:42.195 --> 59:43.685
And he was very rich.

59:44.197 --> 59:45.186
What faith?

59:47.867 --> 59:49.027
My father-in-law...

59:50.203 --> 59:53.366
...was called by God
when he was six or something.

59:55.375 --> 59:59.869
He started preaching, baptized people,
and he saved them and then...

01:00:01.881 --> 01:00:05.783
...he traveled around a lot and
became pretty famous. Not like...

01:00:07.387 --> 01:00:08.877
...some of them but...

01:00:10.556 --> 01:00:12.319
...pretty famous.

01:00:15.228 --> 01:00:17.719
When he died he had a lot of money.

01:00:18.831 --> 01:00:21.391
- God's money?
- No, his own.

01:00:22.468 --> 01:00:26.063
- What about God's money?
- He spent it and he saved his own.

01:00:27.740 --> 01:00:29.230
I think that's very nice.

01:00:32.412 --> 01:00:34.437
Martha has money because...

01:00:34.647 --> 01:00:37.480
...Martha's father's second wife...

01:00:37.684 --> 01:00:40.585
...not Martha's mother,
but after her mother died...

01:00:41.120 --> 01:00:43.111
...was a very old lady...

01:00:43.323 --> 01:00:46.417
...who had warts, who was very rich.

01:00:46.993 --> 01:00:48.392
She was a witch!

01:00:50.063 --> 01:00:53.032
She was a good witch,
and she married the white mouse...

01:00:53.232 --> 01:00:55.530
...with the red eyes,
and he must have...

01:00:55.735 --> 01:00:58.533
...nibbled her warts
or something...

01:01:00.139 --> 01:01:04.166
...because she went up in a
puff of smoke almost immediately.

01:01:06.846 --> 01:01:10.646
And all that was left,
apart from some wart medicine...

01:01:10.850 --> 01:01:13.318
...was a big, fat will.

01:01:18.424 --> 01:01:21.393
Maybe my father-in-law...

01:01:21.627 --> 01:01:24.790
...and the witch with the warts
should have gotten together.

01:01:26.132 --> 01:01:28.123
Because he was a mouse too.

01:01:29.836 --> 01:01:31.770
- He was?
- Sure!

01:01:34.474 --> 01:01:36.305
He was a church mouse!

01:01:53.326 --> 01:01:55.294
Your wife never mentioned a stepmother.

01:01:56.496 --> 01:01:57.724
Maybe it isn't true.

01:01:59.999 --> 01:02:03.162
You realize I've been
drawing you out on this stuff...

01:02:03.870 --> 01:02:07.533
...because you're a threat to me
and I want to get the goods on you.

01:02:07.740 --> 01:02:08.729
Sure.

01:02:09.008 --> 01:02:11.067
I've warned you. You stand warned.

01:02:11.277 --> 01:02:12.835
I stand warned.

01:02:15.281 --> 01:02:18.307
You sneaky types
worry me the most, you know.

01:02:18.518 --> 01:02:21.510
You ineffectual sons of bitches,
you're the worst.

01:02:21.854 --> 01:02:25.620
I'm glad you don't believe me.
You've got history on your side.

01:02:27.026 --> 01:02:30.518
You've got history on your side.
I've got biology on mine.

01:02:31.030 --> 01:02:33.021
History, biology.

01:02:33.366 --> 01:02:35.334
- I know the difference.
- You don't act it.

01:02:35.701 --> 01:02:39.831
We decided you'd take over the History
Department first, then the whole works.

01:02:40.039 --> 01:02:40.869
A step at a time.

01:02:44.410 --> 01:02:49.211
What I thought I'd do is sort of
insinuate myself generally. You know!

01:02:49.549 --> 01:02:51.210
Find all the weak spots.

01:02:52.585 --> 01:02:53.609
Like me.

01:02:54.387 --> 01:02:58.380
Become sort of a fact
and then turn into a...

01:03:00.793 --> 01:03:03.557
- A what?
- An inevitability?

01:03:04.063 --> 01:03:05.155
Exactly!

01:03:05.364 --> 01:03:07.229
An inevitability.

01:03:07.900 --> 01:03:10.562
Take over a few courses
from the older men.

01:03:13.239 --> 01:03:15.230
Plow a few pertinent wives.

01:03:15.575 --> 01:03:16.564
Now that's it!

01:03:17.743 --> 01:03:19.904
You can shove aside
all the older men...

01:03:20.246 --> 01:03:23.409
...but until you're plowing pertinent
wives you're not working.

01:03:23.749 --> 01:03:25.740
That's the way to power. Plow 'em all!

01:03:28.921 --> 01:03:30.252
The way to a man's heart...

01:03:30.590 --> 01:03:34.492
...the wide, inviting avenue to his job
is through his wife...

01:03:34.694 --> 01:03:36.161
...and don't you forget it.

01:03:36.362 --> 01:03:41.095
I bet your wife's got the most inviting
avenue on the whole campus!

01:03:45.104 --> 01:03:47.504
I mean, her father
being president and all.

01:03:48.608 --> 01:03:51.099
You bet your historical inevitability.

01:03:51.944 --> 01:03:54.936
I just better get her off
into the bushes right away.

01:03:55.147 --> 01:03:56.614
You'd certainly better.

01:03:59.619 --> 01:04:01.211
I almost think you're serious.

01:04:02.054 --> 01:04:05.182
No, you almost think you're serious.
And it scares you.

01:04:05.625 --> 01:04:06.387
Me?

01:04:06.959 --> 01:04:07.857
Yes, you.

01:04:08.060 --> 01:04:09.118
You're kidding!

01:04:09.462 --> 01:04:13.125
I wish I were. I'll give you some
good advice if you want me to.

01:04:13.466 --> 01:04:14.933
Good advice? From you?

01:04:15.968 --> 01:04:19.961
You haven't learned yet. Take it
wherever you can get it. Listen.

01:04:21.307 --> 01:04:23.298
I'm giving you good advice now.

01:04:24.977 --> 01:04:28.435
There's quicksand here and you'll be
dragged down before you know it.

01:04:28.648 --> 01:04:29.876
Sucked down!

01:04:31.150 --> 01:04:34.483
You disgust me on principle and you're
a smug son of a bitch...

01:04:34.987 --> 01:04:38.650
...but I'm trying to give you
a survival kit. Do you hear me?

01:04:38.858 --> 01:04:40.621
I hear you. You come in loud.

01:04:40.993 --> 01:04:42.824
You want to play it by ear, right?

01:04:43.162 --> 01:04:46.825
Everything will work out anyway,
because the timetable's history, right?

01:04:47.166 --> 01:04:50.158
Right. Just tend to your knitting,
